      "content": "Yes, there are a few sneaky culprits that are notoriously hard to spot before you even take off, often hiding in plain sight. One of the most common is **insect debris** or \"bugs,\" which can get sucked into the tube during takeoff or landing, especially in warmer months, and form a sticky plug that's impossible to see without looking inside. Another is **paint chips or rust flakes** from the aircraft's own surface, which can accumulate over time and create a slow clog that a quick visual check might miss.\n\nIt's also worth noting that **condensation or moisture** can sometimes freeze inside the tube if there's a draft, creating an internal blockage that doesn't come from the outside. These \"little things\" are why pilots often have a specific pre-flight routine to blow out the pitot tube with compressed air, essentially performing a quick \"flush\" to ensure the sensor is clear before the engine starts.",
